Hey, I wanted to provide some feedback I wrote down as I made my way through the story. Definitely an interesting read, and I hope you'll continue exploring serious themes like this down the road.

A couple things early on: the word choice is sometimes on the plain side, and the intro could stand to amp up the sadness to better hook the reader. Combining these points, I took a stab at trying to perk up the first few sentences. For reference, all numbers are paragraph IDs from Pastebin.
>19: The faint whirring of the overhead fan greeted the griffin as she entered her modest apartment. Despite its inanimate nature, the fan was still the most lively thing to grace the griffin's home in quite some time--at least, as far as she could recall. With a sigh, Mir hung her keys on the wall hook and paced towards the living room. A small jolt ran through her body as she honed in on the muffled laughter and conversation coming from just beyond the thin walls of the unit. Shaking her head, she instinctively moved towards the streaked window to draw the blinds.

Show, don't tell: a common pitfall. Look at 21 for example. You're dictating exactly what Mir (or the omniscient narrator) sees, as opposed to using other senses or indirect descriptions (e.g., instead of her expression turning into a frown, her brow could furrow; she could stroke her beak pensively; she could narrow her gaze to indicate disgust, either with what she's seeing or even herself).

Grammar: An em dash is followed by lowercase for common nouns (23). SEO optimization -> search engine optimization optimization. outlook -> Outlook. May be better able to indicate continuation with a colon (on 29, "...they focused in on a recurring thought: what if there was somebody out there..."). Some other capitalization typos throughout, but doesn't affect readability.

Flow and direction feels good, not jarring.

(cont'd)

You're being overly critical of yourself in my opinion. You already see areas you want to improve or can do better, so apply that to a new piece.
